{"title_page": "Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls", "text_new": "'''Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls''', KB, [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], MD, [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (27 September 1851 - 9 February 1926) was a [[physician]], disease specialist, [[horticulturist]], [[zoologist]] and [[legislator]] in, and [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]] for over 50 years. He published on a wide variety of topics and was awarded a [[knighthood ]]for his services just before his death.\n\n==Biography==\n\nNicholls was born on 27 September 1851 in [[Spitalfields]] and baptised at nearby [[Christ Church, Spitalfields|Christ Church]] on 31 December. He was the eldest of five children of Elizabeth Ann Pitkin and Thomas William Nicholls, a surgical instrument manufacturer.The family lived at 258 [[Kingsland Road]], where Thomas practised his trade; later he was in business there with his second son, Walter James.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Kelly's Post Office London Directory | page = 1220 | publisher = | year = 1891}}</ref>\n\nNicholls attended the [[Davenant Foundation School |Whitechapel Foundation School]]. He entered [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]] Medical College on 25 October 1869<ref>Button, Clare, Archivist, Barts & The London School of Medicine and Dentistry; March 2020</ref> from where, in 1870, he was awarded, in the examination of practical anatomy at [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]], a certificate, examiner\u2019s prize, and the [[Proctor]]ship.<ref>{{cite newspaper | title = Foundation School, Leman Street, Whitechapel | newspaper = Tower Hamlets Independent and East End Local Advertiser | page = 6 | date = 23 April 1870}}</ref> The following year he delivered a lecture at school on \u201cThe digestive system\u201d, concluding a course on physiology.<ref>{{Citation | title = Whitechapel Foundation School Literary and Scientific Society | page = 5 | newspaper = East London Observer | location = | date = 18 November 1871}}</ref> He graduated in medicine ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB]] and [[Doctor of Medicine|CM]]) at the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1873,<ref>{{Citation | title = University of Aberdeen: Degrees in Medicine and Surgery | page = 6 | newspaper = Aberdeen Press and Journal | location = | date = 30 April 1873}}</ref> and gained his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD degree]] from St Bartholomew's Hospital in 1875. Almost immediately he emigrated to [[Dominica]], to serve as Assistant Medical Officer to [[John Imray|Dr John Imray]] who had been there since 1832.\n\nNicholls married Marion Crompton, the \u201cshy and retiring third daughter\u201d<ref name = \"Para\">{{cite book | last = Paravisini-Gebert | first = Lizabeth | title = Phyllis Shand Allfrey: A Caribbean Life | publisher = Rutgers University Press | location = New Brunswick, NJ | date = 1996 | isbn = 0-8135-2264-1}}</ref> of John Corney Crompton and Marianne F\u00e9licit\u00e9 Renault, on 6 September 1877. In the period 1878 to 1891 they had 10 children: 4 boys and 6 girls. The family had two homes. One was at St Aroment - a thirty-acre estate on the outskirts of Roseau, which Nicholls inherited from Dr Imray; the other was Kingsland House, a one-story wooden town house \"with a broad veranda\".<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n===Exploration, and Promotion of Dominica===\n\nVery soon after his arrival in [[Dominica]], Nicholls and three companions went from [[Roseau]] to the interior of the island, in what is now known as [[Morne Trois Pitons National Park]]. There, with the help of their carriers (four men and some boys) they climbed up through heavily forested slopes and found [[Boiling Lake]] \u2013 \u201ca large sheet of water in a constant state of ebullition.\u201d On a second trip, in April, the lake's altitude was found to be 2425 feet (739 metres), and its size about 150 by 80 yards, much smaller than estimated on the first trip.<ref>Nicholls gives two different dates for the discovery: \"January 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = The Boiling Lake of Dominica | pages = 562\u20133 | newspaper = The Field | location = London | date = 5 June 1875}}, and \"March 2nd 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = Boiling Lake at Dominica | pages = | newspaper = The Graphic | location = | date = 9 April 1879}}</ref>\n\nNicholls wrote an article about a volcanic explosion which took place about a mile southwest of [[Boiling Lake]] on 4 January 1880.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls  | first1 = H A Alford |  title = The Volcanic Eruption in Dominica | journal = Nature | volume = 21 | issue = 538 | pages = 372\u20133 | location = London| date = 19 February 1880| doi = 10.1038/021372c0 | bibcode = 1880Natur..21..372N }}</ref> In 1883 he wrote a letter giving a vivid description of the impact of a hurricane on 4 September, with 5 churches destroyed and over 400 families homeless in Roseau.<ref>{{Citation | title = General Foreign News | page = 5 | newspaper = London Evening Standard | location = | date = 29 September 1883}}</ref> In 1902 he gave a detailed account of events associated with the massive eruption of [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]] in Martinique.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Notes on the Recent Eruptions of Mont Pel\u00e9e | journal = Nature | volume = 66 | issue = 1721 | page = 638 | date = 1902| doi = 10.1038/066638b0 | bibcode = 1902Natur..66..638N }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 1880, Nicholls escorted 14 year-old George Prince of Wales (the future King [[George V]]), and his elder brother [[Prince Albert Victor]], first on ponies and then on foot to the \u201chighest point in the island, [[Morne Diablotins|Morne Diablotin]], 5,314 feet high, nearly a thousand feet higher than the highest point in Great Britain, [[Ben Nevis]].\u201d<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Prince of Wales | first1 = George | last2 = Albert Victor | first2 = Prince | last3 = Alton | first3 = John N D | title = The Cruise of [[HMS Bacchante (1876)|H.M.S. \"Bacchante\"]], 1879\u20141882| volume = I | location = London | publisher = Macmillan & Co | page = 133 | date = 1880}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a frequent [[publicist]] for [[Dominica]]. At the [[Colonial and Indian Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] in 1886, he had a large showcase containing samples of many of Dominica\u2019s natural products, including essential oils, [[cocoa]], [[sulphur]], [[bark]], [[coffee]], [[Annatto|annato [''sic'']]] and vanilla. It was \u201ca trophy of ''multum in parvo''\u201d by exhibiting so compactly such a wide range of resources from the island.<ref>{{Citation | title = Colonial and Indian Exhibition | page = 15  | newspaper = St James's Gazette | location = London | date = 27 September 1888}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nOne of Nicholls' first papers after arrival in Dominica was on \"Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear\" in which he differed from a previous correspondent, Mr Walter Rivington (surgeon in charge of the aural department at the London Hospital), on the best approach to adopt, and taking Rivington to task for relying only on syringing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 811 | pages = 75\u20136 | date = 15 July 1876| doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.811.75-a | pmid = 20748266 | pmc = 2297920 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877 Nicholls was appointed Medical Superintendent of the Dominica Yaws Hospital and, when Dr Imray retired, he succeeded him as Medical Officer of Public Institutions in 1880. In 1891 the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] appointed him as Special Commissioner to inquire into the prevalence of [[Yaws|yaws]] in the West Indies.<ref name = \"Noble\">{{cite book | last = Noble | first = His Honour Mr Justice | title = A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, KB, CMG | publisher = The Bulletin Office | location = Roseau, Dominica | date = 1928}}</ref> His report was published as a [[Blue book]] in 1894,<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = Report on Yaws in Tobago, Grenada, St Vincent, St Lucia, and the Leeward Islands| pages = | publisher = Her Majesty's Stationery Office | location = London | date = 1894}}</ref> and won warm praise from the then Secretary of State, [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford|Lord Knutsford]]: \"your report is a monument of your ... ability as a scientific expert\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Following this recognition Nicholls was able to write an authoritative chapter on yaws and its treatment.<ref>{{Citation | first = Henry Alfred Alford | last = Nicholls | title = Yaws | editor-last = Stedman | editor-first = Thomas Lathrop | volume = XVI Infectious Diseases | year = 1899 | place = London | publisher = Sampson Low, Marston and Company}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was editor of ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  | title = Reviews of Books: ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal'' | journal = Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal (1883)| volume = 10 | issue = 35| page = 52 | publisher = The Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Society | location = Bristol | date = March 1892}}</ref> He was also interested in tetanus, malaria and the hookworm disease [[ancylostomiasis]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, CMG, MD | first = H A Alford | title = Anchylostomiasis in the Leeward Islands | journal = Journal of Tropical Medicine | volume = 2 | pages = 247\u2013249 | publisher = John Bale Sons & Danielsson | location = London| date = 1884}}</ref> His most senior appointment before retirement was Principal Medical Officer of Dominica, made in 1922.\n\n===Botany, Horticulture and Zoology===\n\nNicholls was particularly interested in expanding the cultivation of [[coffee]] in [[Dominica]]. In his paper on the subject<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The Cultivation of Liberian Coffee | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana | volume = 3 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1884}}</ref> he began by noting that \"Liberian coffee was introduced into the West Indies from the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Gardens at Kew]] in the year 1874, when a few plants were sent by [[Joseph Dalton Hooker|Sir Joseph Hooker]] to the Botanic Gardens at [[Jamaica]] and [[Trinidad]], and to the late Dr Imray of Dominica.\" He goes on to describe the preferred soils and the need for shelter trees to protect from hurricanes.\n\nIn the early 1880s - during Hooker's last few years as Director of Kew - Nicholls was the Kew correspondent for Dominica. For that reason Nicholls dedicated his ''Text-Book on Tropical Agriculture'' to Sir Joseph.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = A Text-Book of Tropical Agriculture | pages = | publisher = Macmillan and Co. Ltd. | location = London | date = 1892}}</ref> The demand for it was such that the book was reprinted seven times at intervals of about five years; it was also translated into several languages along with [[Swiss]]-[[Venezuelan]] [[geographer]] and [[botanist]] [[Henri Fran\u00e7ois Pittier]]. Nicholls wrote many letters to Hooker, [[William Turner Thiselton-Dyer|Sir William Thiselton-Dyer]], [[Daniel Morris (botanist)|Daniel Morris]] and others at Kew.<ref>{{cite web | title = Archive Catalogue | website = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | publisher =  | date =  | url = http://www.calmview.eu/kew/calmview/Overview.aspx | access-date = 18 February 2020}}</ref> He also contributed plants and seeds to the collection there.<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = A List of the Collectors Whose Plants Are in the Herbarium of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, to 31st December, 1899 | journal = Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information | volume = 1901 | page = 49 | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | location = Kew | date = 1901}}</ref>\n\nSoon after his election as a Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]] (CMZS), Nicholls donated two common [[Boidae|boas]] and seven slender-fingered [[frogs]] to the zoo.<ref name = \"ZSL\">Broadhurst, Sarah, Archivist and Records Manager, Zoological Society of London, February 2020</ref>\n\nNicholls' passion for expanding the export of fruit was expressed in his booklet on ''The cultivation of the banana in Dominica''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The cultivation of the banana in Dominica | pages = | publisher = A.T. Righton, Printer to the Govt. | location = | date = 1890}}</ref> He noted that now that [[Dominica]] had become the last port of call by the Quebec Steamship Company on its West Indies to New York line \"there is no reason why the planters of the island should not participate in the profits from the banana trade\", which currently was dominated by Jamaica. With his usual clarity and precision he went on to describe the conditions necessary for successful  propagation of the fruit.\n\nIn 1887, [[James Anthony Froude]] travelled to the West Indies. During his visit to [[Dominica]] he was invited by Nicholls to visit his home, where he saw the very successful cultivation of lime trees:\n{{Quote |text= I do not know the exact extent of the property which was under cultivation; perhaps it was twenty-five or thirty acres. The chief part of it was planted with lime trees, the limes which I saw growing being as large as moderate-sized lemons; most of the rest was covered with Liberian coffee, which does not object to the moist climate, and was growing with profuse luxuriance. Each tree, each plant had been personally attended to, pruned when it needed pruning, supported by bamboos if it was overgrowing its strength, while the ground about the house was consecrated to botanical experiments, and specimens were to be seen there of every tropical flower, shrub, or tree, which was either remarkable for its beauty or valuable for its chemical properties. His limes and coffee went principally to New York, where they had won a reputation, and were in special demand; but ingenuity tries other tracks besides the beaten one. Dr. Nicholls had a manufactory of [[Citric acid|citric acid]] which had been found equally excellent in Europe. Everything which he produced was turning to gold, except donkeys, seven or eight of which were feeding under his windows, and which multiplied so fast that he could not tell what to do with them. |author=James Anthony Froude |title= |source= ''The English in the West Indies'' (1888)<ref>{{cite book | last = Froude | first = James Anthony | title = The English in the West Indies: Or, The Bow of Ulysses | pages = | publisher = Longmans, Green, and Co | location = London | date = 1888}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1889 [[The Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana]] sought and received advice on the packing of fruit for export. Nicholls gave precise instructions on when and how to cut [[oranges]] and [[limes]], wrap them in a special paper, and pack them in specific designs of crate or barrel. His instructions were later printed for distribution.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Quelch | first = J J | title = Letter on the packing of fruit for shipment | journal = Timehri | volume = 3 (New Series) | pages = 172\u2013174 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1889}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliations, Appointments and Awards===\n\n*Corresponding Member of the [[New York Academy of Sciences]]. Elected 1882.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fairchild | first = Herman Le Roy | title = A History of the New York Academy of Sciences | pages = | publisher = Herman Le Roy Fairchild | location = New York | date = 1887}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the [[Linnean Society of London|Linnean Society]]. Elected 21 June 1883.<ref>Thorne, Luke:  Assistant Archivist, The Linnean Society, February 2020</ref>\n*Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Elected 19 January 1888.<ref name = \"ZSL\"/>\n*Honorary Member of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]]<ref>{{cite journal | last = Thurn, MA | first = E F Im | title = Elections: Honorary Members | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]] | volume = 5 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1886}}</ref>\n*CMG: Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]]. 1 January 1896<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = Appointments to the Most Distinguished Order of Saint Michael and Saint George | journal = Supplement to the London Gazette | volume = 26695 | page = 2 | location = London| date = 1 January 1896}}</ref>\n*Chairman of the Roseau Town Board. 1896-98.<ref name = \"Garvey\">{{cite book | last = Garvey| first = Marcus | title = The Marcus Garvey and Universal Negro Improvement Association Papers | pages = | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham, NC | date = 2011 | isbn = 978-0-8223-4690-6}}</ref>\n*Official Member of the Legislative Council of Dominica. From 1898.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*Vice-President of the Dominica Agricultural Society<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = The Weather Bureau in Dominica, W.I. | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 28  | issue = 6|  page = 252 | publisher = War Department, Office of the Chief Signal Officer | date = June 1900| doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1900)28[252a:TWBIDW]2.0.CO;2| bibcode = 1900MWRv...28Q.252.}}</ref>\n*Silver cup presented to him in 1914 by the [[West India Committee]] for the best individual Exhibit of Tropical Produce from the [[British West Indies]], [[British Guiana]] or [[British Honduras]]<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n*War work - Food Prices Committee. 1914-1919.<ref>{{cite book | title =  University of Aberdeen Roll of Service in the Great War, 1914-1919| page = 327 | publisher = Aberdeen University Press | location = Aberdeen | date = 1921 }}</ref>\n*Joined the Executive Council of the Leeward Islands. 1922.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*[[Knighthood]]. Conferred 1 January 1926.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = St. James's Palace, S.W.1, 1st January 1926 | journal = The Edinburgh Gazette | volume = 14193 | page = 3 | date = 1 January 1926}}</ref>\n\nHenry Nicholls learned of his knighthood by telegram from the Governor of Dominica: \"It gives me much pleasure to inform you that His Majesty has been graciously pleased to approve of K.B. (Knight Bachelor) Nicholls. Please convey my hearty congratulations.\" The event was celebrated at a gathering of Sir Henry & Lady Nicholls and relatives at Government House, at which [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and Nicholls' grandson by marriage, said:\n\n{{Quote\n| text = Sir Henry and Lady Nicholls,\nI feel it a great privilege to-day to convey to you, in the presence of your family and old friends, the King\u2019s gracious pleasure in conferring on you, Sir, the Honour of Knighthood [...] We deplore, Sir, the bodily suffering which has been your lot in your well earned rest period, realising as we do that present loss of health is due to the years of faithful toil which you have given to this Presidency. We pray that your health may be restored, and that you and Lady Nicholls may be spared to us in health and happiness for years to come.<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n}}\n\nSadly, Sir Henry died on 9 February 1926. Condolences were received from far and wide, including Sir Algernon Edward Aspinall, Secretary of the West India Committee, [[J. P. Morgan Jr.|J Pierpoint Morgan Jr]] who was visiting Trinidad and J H Menzies in Canada, who wrote of Nicholls in an article entitled \"The Uncrowned King of Dominica\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Menzies | first1 = J H |  title = The Uncrowned King of Dominica | journal = United Empire | volume = 17 | page = 203 | publisher = Pitman and Sons Ltd | location = London | date = 1926}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a leading member of the Anglican Church. After an impressive funeral, with many public figures attending, he was, as a mark of honour, \"buried next to the church in Roseau rather than in the general church graveyard some distance away at Newtown.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Honychurch | first1 = Lennox | title = A - Z of Dominica heritage | edition = | location = Rouseau, Dominica | publisher = The Chronicle | pages = | date = 2001}}</ref> The white marble cross bears the inscription \"Life\u2019s Work Well Done. Then Comes Rest\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/>.\n\n===Some Nicholls children and their descendants===\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 second daughter, Elfreda Millicent (1883-1955), married Francis Byam Berkeley Shand on 27 March 1905, at \u201cRoseau\u2019s social event of the year\u201d.<ref name = \"Para\"/> Shand was to become Crown Attorney of Dominica.<ref>{{cite book | title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 85th Congress, Second Session Volume 104, Part 6 | page = 7295 | publisher = United States Government Printing Service | location = Washington, DC | date = 1958 }}</ref> Their daughter [[Phyllis Shand Allfrey]] was a prominent figure on the island, founder of the [[Dominica Labour Party]], and author of [[The Orchid House (novel)|''The Orchid House'']]. Francis and Elfreda\u2019s eldest daughter, Alice Marion, married [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and 37 years her senior.\n\n*Elfreda\u2019s younger brother, Ralph Edgar Alford (1885-1945), \u201cthe [[black sheep]] of the Nicholls family\u201d,<ref name = \"Para\"/> had five children by two women: Margaret Evelyn Royer and Clayron Royer, probably sisters. Clayron\u2019s daughter, Rosalind, married Cyril Frederick Louis Volney. Their son, Herbert Philip, was an MP in the 10th Republican Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago for 5 years until 17 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of Past Parliaments: Mr. Herbert Volney, MP  | website = Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago | publisher = Office of the Parliament, Port of Spain | date = | url = http://www.ttparliament.org/members.php?mid=26&pid=25&id=HEV10 | access-date = 3 March 2020}}</ref> Ralph was a Freemason; he was initiated into the St George Lodge, Roseau in 1910.<ref>United Grand Lodge of England Freemason Membership Registers, 1751-1921</ref>\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 youngest son, William Alford (1891-1970) was sent to [[Scotland]] to study medicine. In 1914 he joined the [[Royal Army Medical Corps|RAMC]]. The following year he was transferred to the [[Royal Artillery]] and served in [[France]] until 1919. He then re-enlisted in the RAMC, served in [[Egypt]] for three years, and returned to [[England]]. He found a job as a clerk but lost it through absence on a bout of drinking.\n\n:In 1927 he was sentenced by the magistrate, [[Herbert Wilberforce]], in [[Marylebone ]] to six months\u2019 hard labour, having pleaded guilty to charges of stealing a suit belonging to a fellow lodger, and obtaining money fraudulently from three police constables in London.<ref>{{Citation| title = Imposed on by Doctor's son | page = 7 | newspaper = West London Observer | date = 7 August 1925 }}</ref> Nicholls had already been imprisoned for 3 months in 1924 for stealing a suit from a room mate.<ref>{{Citation | title = Robbed his Room Mate| page = 3 | newspaper = West London Observer | location = | date = 26 December 1924}}</ref>\n\n:In the 1950s and 60s the electoral registers showed that William lived at 53 Lulworth House,Dorset Road,[[Vauxhall]]. He was entered twice, under slightly different names, and with up to four women with him. The 1957 register shows all four:\n\n::Nicholls, Barbara D.\n::Nicholls, Dorothy A.\n::Nicholls, Joyce P.\n::Nicholls, Pamela R.\n::Nicholls, William Alford\n::Nicholls, William Alfred\n\nWilliam Alford Nicholls died in the Westminster registration district in 1970. There is no record of a marriage.\n\n=== Sir Henry Nicholls' Legacy===\n\n*[[Morne Nicholls]], elevation 3,168 feet (966 metres), named after him.\n*[[Tree Bat]] ''Ardops nichollsi'' named after him<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Beolens | first = Bo | last2 = Watkins | first2 = Michael | last3 = Grayson | first3 = Michael  | title = The Eponym Dictionary of Mammals | page = 292 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, MD | isbn = 9780801893049 | date = 2009}}</ref> \n*Ward named after him at [[Princess Margaret Hospital]], [[Roseau]]\n*Books from his collection added to a library reflecting the cultural and historical heritage of the Caribbean<ref>{{cite document | last = Joseph | first = Jennifer M. | last2 = Vacianna | first2 = Joan | title = Resources on Caribbean Cultural Identity: Documentation, Preservation and Access | publisher = | date = 10\u201314 August 2008 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.150.7178 }}</ref>\n*''A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, K. B., C.M.G.'', by His Honour Mr. Justice Noble (1928).<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Noble begins his memoir \"Many of the leading citizens of Dominica have expressed their desire to have some short memoir of their late friend Sir Henry Nicholls published. In response to such an appeal it would seem only proper that a brief description of his work and career should be attempted.\"\n\nAs a final tribute to the Nicholls family, some of the characters in ''[[The Orchid House]]'' are clearly inspired by them at their home at L\u2019Aromatique, with Old Master being Nicholls himself, and Rufus the errant Ralph.<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Dominica]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in the Caribbean]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls''', KB, [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], MD, [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] (27 September 1851 - 9 February 1926) was a physician, disease specialist, horticulturist, zoologist and legislator in, and publicist for Dominica for over 50 years. He published on a wide variety of topics and was awarded a knighthood for his services just before his death.\n\n==Biography==\n\nNicholls was born on 27 September 1851 in [[Spitalfields]] and baptised at nearby [[Christ Church, Spitalfields|Christ Church]] on 31 December. He was the eldest of five children of Elizabeth Ann Pitkin and Thomas William Nicholls, a surgical instrument manufacturer.The family lived at 258 Kingsland Road, where Thomas practised his trade; later he was in business there with his second son, Walter James.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Kelly's Post Office London Directory | page = 1220 | publisher = | year = 1891}}</ref>\n\nNicholls attended the [[Davenant Foundation School |Whitechapel Foundation School]]. He entered [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]] Medical College on 25 October 1869<ref>Button, Clare, Archivist, Barts & The London School of Medicine and Dentistry; March 2020</ref> from where, in 1870, he was awarded, in the examination of practical anatomy at [[St Bartholomew\u2019s Hospital]], a certificate, examiner\u2019s prize, and the [[Proctor]]ship.<ref>{{cite newspaper | title = Foundation School, Leman Street, Whitechapel | newspaper = Tower Hamlets Independent and East End Local Advertiser | page = 6 | date = 23 April 1870}}</ref> The following year he delivered a lecture at school on \u201cThe digestive system\u201d, concluding a course on physiology.<ref>{{Citation | title = Whitechapel Foundation School Literary and Scientific Society | page = 5 | newspaper = East London Observer | location = | date = 18 November 1871}}</ref> He graduated in medicine ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|MB]] and [[Doctor of Medicine|CM]]) at the University of Aberdeen in 1873,<ref>{{Citation | title = University of Aberdeen: Degrees in Medicine and Surgery | page = 6 | newspaper = Aberdeen Press and Journal | location = | date = 30 April 1873}}</ref> and gained his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD degree]] from St Bartholomew's Hospital in 1875. Almost immediately he emigrated to [[Dominica]], to serve as Assistant Medical Officer to [[John Imray|Dr John Imray]] who had been there since 1832.\n\nNicholls married Marion Crompton, the \u201cshy and retiring third daughter\u201d<ref name = \"Para\">{{cite book | last = Paravisini-Gebert | first = Lizabeth | title = Phyllis Shand Allfrey: A Caribbean Life | publisher = Rutgers University Press | location = New Brunswick, NJ | date = 1996 | isbn = 0-8135-2264-1}}</ref> of John Corney Crompton and Marianne F\u00e9licit\u00e9 Renault, on 6 September 1877. In the period 1878 to 1891 they had 10 children: 4 boys and 6 girls. The family had two homes. One was at St Aroment - a thirty-acre estate on the outskirts of Roseau, which Nicholls inherited from Dr Imray; the other was Kingsland House, a one-story wooden town house \"with a broad veranda\".<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n===Exploration, and Promotion of Dominica===\n\nVery soon after his arrival in [[Dominica]], Nicholls and three companions went from [[Roseau]] to the interior of the island, in what is now known as [[Morne Trois Pitons National Park]]. There, with the help of their carriers (four men and some boys) they climbed up through heavily forested slopes and found [[Boiling Lake]] \u2013 \u201ca large sheet of water in a constant state of ebullition.\u201d On a second trip, in April, the lake's altitude was found to be 2425 feet (739 metres), and its size about 150 by 80 yards, much smaller than estimated on the first trip.<ref>Nicholls gives two different dates for the discovery: \"January 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = The Boiling Lake of Dominica | pages = 562\u20133 | newspaper = The Field | location = London | date = 5 June 1875}}, and \"March 2nd 1875\" in {{Cite news | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = Boiling Lake at Dominica | pages = | newspaper = The Graphic | location = | date = 9 April 1879}}</ref>\n\nNicholls wrote an article about a volcanic explosion which took place about a mile southwest of [[Boiling Lake]] on 4 January 1880.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls  | first1 = H A Alford |  title = The Volcanic Eruption in Dominica | journal = Nature | volume = 21 | issue = 538 | pages = 372\u20133 | location = London| date = 19 February 1880| doi = 10.1038/021372c0 | bibcode = 1880Natur..21..372N }}</ref> In 1883 he wrote a letter giving a vivid description of the impact of a hurricane on 4 September, with 5 churches destroyed and over 400 families homeless in Roseau.<ref>{{Citation | title = General Foreign News | page = 5 | newspaper = London Evening Standard | location = | date = 29 September 1883}}</ref> In 1902 he gave a detailed account of events associated with the massive eruption of [[Mount Pel\u00e9e]] in Martinique.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Notes on the Recent Eruptions of Mont Pel\u00e9e | journal = Nature | volume = 66 | issue = 1721 | page = 638 | date = 1902| doi = 10.1038/066638b0 | bibcode = 1902Natur..66..638N }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 1880, Nicholls escorted 14 year-old George Prince of Wales (the future King [[George V]]), and his elder brother [[Prince Albert Victor]], first on ponies and then on foot to the \u201chighest point in the island, [[Morne Diablotins|Morne Diablotin]], 5,314 feet high, nearly a thousand feet higher than the highest point in Great Britain, [[Ben Nevis]].\u201d<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Prince of Wales | first1 = George | last2 = Albert Victor | first2 = Prince | last3 = Alton | first3 = John N D | title = The Cruise of [[HMS Bacchante (1876)|H.M.S. \"Bacchante\"]], 1879\u20141882| volume = I | location = London | publisher = Macmillan & Co | page = 133 | date = 1880}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a frequent publicist for Dominica. At the [[Colonial and Indian Exhibition]] in [[South Kensington]] in 1886, he had a large showcase containing samples of many of Dominica\u2019s natural products, including essential oils, cocoa, sulphur, bark, coffee, [[Annatto|annato [''sic'']]] and vanilla. It was \u201ca trophy of ''multum in parvo''\u201d by exhibiting so compactly such a wide range of resources from the island.<ref>{{Citation | title = Colonial and Indian Exhibition | page = 15  | newspaper = St James's Gazette | location = London | date = 27 September 1888}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\nOne of Nicholls' first papers after arrival in Dominica was on \"Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear\" in which he differed from a previous correspondent, Mr Walter Rivington (surgeon in charge of the aural department at the London Hospital), on the best approach to adopt, and taking Rivington to task for relying only on syringing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Nicholls| first1 = H A Alford | title = Extraction of Foreign Bodies from the Ear | journal = British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 811 | pages = 75\u20136 | date = 15 July 1876| doi = 10.1136/bmj.2.811.75-a | pmid = 20748266 | pmc = 2297920 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877 Nicholls was appointed Medical Superintendent of the Dominica Yaws Hospital and, when Dr Imray retired, he succeeded him as Medical Officer of Public Institutions in 1880. In 1891 the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] appointed him as Special Commissioner to inquire into the prevalence of [[Yaws|yaws]] in the West Indies.<ref name = \"Noble\">{{cite book | last = Noble | first = His Honour Mr Justice | title = A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, KB, CMG | publisher = The Bulletin Office | location = Roseau, Dominica | date = 1928}}</ref> His report was published as a [[Blue book]] in 1894,<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = Report on Yaws in Tobago, Grenada, St Vincent, St Lucia, and the Leeward Islands| pages = | publisher = Her Majesty's Stationery Office | location = London | date = 1894}}</ref> and won warm praise from the then Secretary of State, [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford|Lord Knutsford]]: \"your report is a monument of your ... ability as a scientific expert\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Following this recognition Nicholls was able to write an authoritative chapter on yaws and its treatment.<ref>{{Citation | first = Henry Alfred Alford | last = Nicholls | title = Yaws | editor-last = Stedman | editor-first = Thomas Lathrop | volume = XVI Infectious Diseases | year = 1899 | place = London | publisher = Sampson Low, Marston and Company}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was editor of ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal''.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  | title = Reviews of Books: ''The Leeward Islands Medical Journal'' | journal = Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Journal (1883)| volume = 10 | issue = 35| page = 52 | publisher = The Bristol Medico-Chirurgical Society | location = Bristol | date = March 1892}}</ref> He was also interested in tetanus, malaria and the hookworm disease [[ancylostomiasis]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, CMG, MD | first = H A Alford | title = Anchylostomiasis in the Leeward Islands | journal = Journal of Tropical Medicine | volume = 2 | pages = 247\u2013249 | publisher = John Bale Sons & Danielsson | location = London| date = 1884}}</ref> His most senior appointment before retirement was Principal Medical Officer of Dominica, made in 1922.\n\n===Botany, Horticulture and Zoology===\n\nNicholls was particularly interested in expanding the cultivation of coffee in Dominica. In his paper on the subject<ref>{{cite journal | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The Cultivation of Liberian Coffee | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana | volume = 3 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1884}}</ref> he began by noting that \"Liberian coffee was introduced into the West Indies from the [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|Royal Gardens at Kew]] in the year 1874, when a few plants were sent by [[Joseph Dalton Hooker|Sir Joseph Hooker]] to the Botanic Gardens at [[Jamaica]] and [[Trinidad]], and to the late Dr Imray of Dominica.\" He goes on to describe the preferred soils and the need for shelter trees to protect from hurricanes.\n\nIn the early 1880s - during Hooker's last few years as Director of Kew - Nicholls was the Kew correspondent for Dominica. For that reason Nicholls dedicated his ''Text-Book on Tropical Agriculture'' to Sir Joseph.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls | first = H A Alford | title = A Text-Book of Tropical Agriculture | pages = | publisher = Macmillan and Co. Ltd. | location = London | date = 1892}}</ref> The demand for it was such that the book was reprinted seven times at intervals of about five years; it was also translated into several languages along with [[Swiss]]-[[Venezuelan]] [[geographer]] and [[botanist]] [[Henri Fran\u00e7ois Pittier]]. Nicholls wrote many letters to Hooker, [[William Turner Thiselton-Dyer|Sir William Thiselton-Dyer]], [[Daniel Morris (botanist)|Daniel Morris]] and others at Kew.<ref>{{cite web | title = Archive Catalogue | website = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | publisher =  | date =  | url = http://www.calmview.eu/kew/calmview/Overview.aspx | access-date = 18 February 2020}}</ref> He also contributed plants and seeds to the collection there.<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = A List of the Collectors Whose Plants Are in the Herbarium of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, to 31st December, 1899 | journal = Bulletin of Miscellaneous Information | volume = 1901 | page = 49 | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | location = Kew | date = 1901}}</ref>\n\nSoon after his election as a Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]] (CMZS), Nicholls donated two common [[Boidae|boas]] and seven slender-fingered [[frogs]] to the zoo.<ref name = \"ZSL\">Broadhurst, Sarah, Archivist and Records Manager, Zoological Society of London, February 2020</ref>\n\nNicholls' passion for expanding the export of fruit was expressed in his booklet on ''The cultivation of the banana in Dominica''.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nicholls, MD, FLS | first = H A Alford | title = The cultivation of the banana in Dominica | pages = | publisher = A.T. Righton, Printer to the Govt. | location = | date = 1890}}</ref> He noted that now that Dominica had become the last port of call by the Quebec Steamship Company on its West Indies to New York line \"there is no reason why the planters of the island should not participate in the profits from the banana trade\", which currently was dominated by Jamaica. With his usual clarity and precision he went on to describe the conditions necessary for successful  propagation of the fruit.\n\nIn 1887, [[James Anthony Froude]] travelled to the West Indies. During his visit to Dominica he was invited by Nicholls to visit his home, where he saw the very successful cultivation of lime trees:\n{{Quote |text= I do not know the exact extent of the property which was under cultivation; perhaps it was twenty-five or thirty acres. The chief part of it was planted with lime trees, the limes which I saw growing being as large as moderate-sized lemons; most of the rest was covered with Liberian coffee, which does not object to the moist climate, and was growing with profuse luxuriance. Each tree, each plant had been personally attended to, pruned when it needed pruning, supported by bamboos if it was overgrowing its strength, while the ground about the house was consecrated to botanical experiments, and specimens were to be seen there of every tropical flower, shrub, or tree, which was either remarkable for its beauty or valuable for its chemical properties. His limes and coffee went principally to New York, where they had won a reputation, and were in special demand; but ingenuity tries other tracks besides the beaten one. Dr. Nicholls had a manufactory of [[Citric acid|citric acid]] which had been found equally excellent in Europe. Everything which he produced was turning to gold, except donkeys, seven or eight of which were feeding under his windows, and which multiplied so fast that he could not tell what to do with them. |author=James Anthony Froude |title= |source= ''The English in the West Indies'' (1888)<ref>{{cite book | last = Froude | first = James Anthony | title = The English in the West Indies: Or, The Bow of Ulysses | pages = | publisher = Longmans, Green, and Co | location = London | date = 1888}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1889 [[The Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of British Guiana]] sought and received advice on the packing of fruit for export. Nicholls gave precise instructions on when and how to cut oranges and limes, wrap them in a special paper, and pack them in specific designs of crate or barrel. His instructions were later printed for distribution.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Quelch | first = J J | title = Letter on the packing of fruit for shipment | journal = Timehri | volume = 3 (New Series) | pages = 172\u2013174 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1889}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliations, Appointments and Awards===\n\n*Corresponding Member of the [[New York Academy of Sciences]]. Elected 1882.<ref>{{cite book | last = Fairchild | first = Herman Le Roy | title = A History of the New York Academy of Sciences | pages = | publisher = Herman Le Roy Fairchild | location = New York | date = 1887}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the [[Linnean Society of London|Linnean Society]]. Elected 21 June 1883.<ref>Thorne, Luke:  Assistant Archivist, The Linnean Society, February 2020</ref>\n*Corresponding Member of the [[Zoological Society of London]]. Elected 19 January 1888.<ref name = \"ZSL\"/>\n*Honorary Member of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]]<ref>{{cite journal | last = Thurn, MA | first = E F Im | title = Elections: Honorary Members | journal = Timehri : Being the Journal of the Royal Agricultural and Commercial Society of [[British Guiana]] | volume = 5 | pages = 286\u2013307 | publisher = J Thomson | location = Demerara | date = 1886}}</ref>\n*CMG: Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]]. 1 January 1896<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = Appointments to the Most Distinguished Order of Saint Michael and Saint George | journal = Supplement to the London Gazette | volume = 26695 | page = 2 | location = London| date = 1 January 1896}}</ref>\n*Chairman of the Roseau Town Board. 1896-98.<ref name = \"Garvey\">{{cite book | last = Garvey| first = Marcus | title = The Marcus Garvey and Universal Negro Improvement Association Papers | pages = | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham, NC | date = 2011 | isbn = 978-0-8223-4690-6}}</ref>\n*Official Member of the Legislative Council of Dominica. From 1898.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*Vice-President of the Dominica Agricultural Society<ref>{{cite journal | last =  | first =  | title = The Weather Bureau in Dominica, W.I. | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 28  | issue = 6|  page = 252 | publisher = War Department, Office of the Chief Signal Officer | date = June 1900| doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1900)28[252a:TWBIDW]2.0.CO;2| bibcode = 1900MWRv...28Q.252.}}</ref>\n*Silver cup presented to him in 1914 by the [[West India Committee]] for the best individual Exhibit of Tropical Produce from the [[British West Indies]], [[British Guiana]] or [[British Honduras]]<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n*War work - Food Prices Committee. 1914-1919.<ref>{{cite book | title =  University of Aberdeen Roll of Service in the Great War, 1914-1919| page = 327 | publisher = Aberdeen University Press | location = Aberdeen | date = 1921 }}</ref>\n*Joined the Executive Council of the Leeward Islands. 1922.<ref name = \"Garvey\"/>\n*Knighthood. Conferred 1 January 1926.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 =  | first1 =  |  title = St. James's Palace, S.W.1, 1st January 1926 | journal = The Edinburgh Gazette | volume = 14193 | page = 3 | date = 1 January 1926}}</ref>\n\nHenry Nicholls learned of his knighthood by telegram from the Governor of Dominica: \"It gives me much pleasure to inform you that His Majesty has been graciously pleased to approve of K.B. (Knight Bachelor) Nicholls. Please convey my hearty congratulations.\" The event was celebrated at a gathering of Sir Henry & Lady Nicholls and relatives at Government House, at which [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and Nicholls' grandson by marriage, said:\n\n{{Quote\n| text = Sir Henry and Lady Nicholls,\nI feel it a great privilege to-day to convey to you, in the presence of your family and old friends, the King\u2019s gracious pleasure in conferring on you, Sir, the Honour of Knighthood [...] We deplore, Sir, the bodily suffering which has been your lot in your well earned rest period, realising as we do that present loss of health is due to the years of faithful toil which you have given to this Presidency. We pray that your health may be restored, and that you and Lady Nicholls may be spared to us in health and happiness for years to come.<ref name = \"Noble\"/>\n}}\n\nSadly, Sir Henry died on 9 February 1926. Condolences were received from far and wide, including Sir Algernon Edward Aspinall, Secretary of the West India Committee, [[J. P. Morgan Jr.|J Pierpoint Morgan Jr]] who was visiting Trinidad and J H Menzies in Canada, who wrote of Nicholls in an article entitled \"The Uncrowned King of Dominica\".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Menzies | first1 = J H |  title = The Uncrowned King of Dominica | journal = United Empire | volume = 17 | page = 203 | publisher = Pitman and Sons Ltd | location = London | date = 1926}}</ref>\n\nNicholls was a leading member of the Anglican Church. After an impressive funeral, with many public figures attending, he was, as a mark of honour, \"buried next to the church in Roseau rather than in the general church graveyard some distance away at Newtown.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Honychurch | first1 = Lennox | title = A - Z of Dominica heritage | edition = | location = Rouseau, Dominica | publisher = The Chronicle | pages = | date = 2001}}</ref> The white marble cross bears the inscription \"Life\u2019s Work Well Done. Then Comes Rest\".<ref name = \"Noble\"/>.\n\n===Some Nicholls children and their descendants===\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 second daughter, Elfreda Millicent (1883-1955), married Francis Byam Berkeley Shand on 27 March 1905, at \u201cRoseau\u2019s social event of the year\u201d.<ref name = \"Para\"/> Shand was to become Crown Attorney of Dominica.<ref>{{cite book | title = Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates of the 85th Congress, Second Session Volume 104, Part 6 | page = 7295 | publisher = United States Government Printing Service | location = Washington, DC | date = 1958 }}</ref> Their daughter [[Phyllis Shand Allfrey]] was a prominent figure on the island, founder of the [[Dominica Labour Party]], and author of [[The Orchid House (novel)|''The Orchid House'']]. Francis and Elfreda\u2019s eldest daughter, Alice Marion, married [[Edward Carlyon Eliot]], Administrator of Dominica and 37 years her senior.\n\n*Elfreda\u2019s younger brother, Ralph Edgar Alford (1885-1945), \u201cthe black sheep of the Nicholls family\u201d,<ref name = \"Para\"/> had five children by two women: Margaret Evelyn Royer and Clayron Royer, probably sisters. Clayron\u2019s daughter, Rosalind, married Cyril Frederick Louis Volney. Their son, Herbert Philip, was an MP in the 10th Republican Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago for 5 years until 17 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of Past Parliaments: Mr. Herbert Volney, MP  | website = Parliament of Trinidad and Tobago | publisher = Office of the Parliament, Port of Spain | date = | url = http://www.ttparliament.org/members.php?mid=26&pid=25&id=HEV10 | access-date = 3 March 2020}}</ref> Ralph was a Freemason; he was initiated into the St George Lodge, Roseau in 1910.<ref>United Grand Lodge of England Freemason Membership Registers, 1751-1921</ref>\n\n*The Nicholls\u2019 youngest son, William Alford (1891-1970) was sent to Scotland to study medicine. In 1914 he joined the [[Royal Army Medical Corps|RAMC]]. The following year he was transferred to the [[Royal Artillery]] and served in France until 1919. He then re-enlisted in the RAMC, served in Egypt for three years, and returned to England. He found a job as a clerk but lost it through absence on a bout of drinking.\n\n:In 1927 he was sentenced by the magistrate, [[Herbert Wilberforce]], in [[Marylebone ]] to six months\u2019 hard labour, having pleaded guilty to charges of stealing a suit belonging to a fellow lodger, and obtaining money fraudulently from three police constables in London.<ref>{{Citation| title = Imposed on by Doctor's son | page = 7 | newspaper = West London Observer | date = 7 August 1925 }}</ref> Nicholls had already been imprisoned for 3 months in 1924 for stealing a suit from a room mate.<ref>{{Citation | title = Robbed his Room Mate| page = 3 | newspaper = West London Observer | location = | date = 26 December 1924}}</ref>\n\n:In the 1950s and 60s the electoral registers showed that William lived at 53 Lulworth House, Dorset Road, [[Vauxhall]]. He was entered twice, under slightly different names, and with up to four women with him. The 1957 register shows all four:\n\n::Nicholls, Barbara D.\n::Nicholls, Dorothy A.\n::Nicholls, Joyce P.\n::Nicholls, Pamela R.\n::Nicholls, William Alford\n::Nicholls, William Alfred\n\nWilliam Alford Nicholls died in the Westminster registration district in 1970. There is no record of a marriage.\n\n=== Sir Henry Nicholls' Legacy===\n\n*[[Morne Nicholls]], elevation 3,168 feet (966 metres), named after him.\n*Tree Bat ''Ardops nichollsi'' named after him<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Beolens | first = Bo | last2 = Watkins | first2 = Michael | last3 = Grayson | first3 = Michael  | title = The Eponym Dictionary of Mammals | page = 292 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press | location = Baltimore, MD | isbn = 9780801893049 | date = 2009}}</ref> \n*Ward named after him at Princess Margaret Hospital, Roseau\n*Books from his collection added to a library reflecting the cultural and historical heritage of the Caribbean<ref>{{cite document | last = Joseph | first = Jennifer M. | last2 = Vacianna | first2 = Joan | title = Resources on Caribbean Cultural Identity: Documentation, Preservation and Access | publisher = | date = 10\u201314 August 2008 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.150.7178 }}</ref>\n*''A Brief Memoir of Sir Henry Alfred Alford Nicholls, K. B., C.M.G.'', by His Honour Mr. Justice Noble (1928).<ref name = \"Noble\"/> Noble begins his memoir \"Many of the leading citizens of Dominica have expressed their desire to have some short memoir of their late friend Sir Henry Nicholls published. In response to such an appeal it would seem only proper that a brief description of his work and career should be attempted.\"\n\nAs a final tribute to the Nicholls family, some of the characters in ''The Orchid House'' are clearly inspired by them at their home at L\u2019Aromatique, with Old Master being Nicholls himself, and Rufus the errant Ralph.<ref name = \"Para\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Dominica]]\n[[Category:Botanists active in the Caribbean]]\n", "name_user": "Bbbrackets", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added brackets to words", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Alfred_Alford_Nicholls"}
{"title_page": "List of vegetarian festivals", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Update|[[American Vegan Society]], which reported on 1/20/2018 that \"Over 120 VegFests in the United States are planned for 2018\", and this article only lists a few of them<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanvegan.org/vegfests.htm|title=Vegfests|website=Americanvegan.org|accessdate=23 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180122071820/http://americanvegan.org/vegfests.htm|archive-date=22 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>|date=February 2019}}  \n{{advert|date=March 2018}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=January 2018}}\n{{Update|The article requires a COUNT of the number of such vegetarian festivals in each continent, and in the USA, for which the largest list of events seems to be presented.|date=October 2019}}\n}}\n\nThis is a global '''list of vegetarian and vegan festivals''', held in numerous locations around the planet, to promote veganism and/or vegetarianism among the public and to support and link individuals and organizations that practice, promote or endorse veganism or vegetarianism. Many of these events are also [[food festivals]] and/or [[music festivals]] and can also contain [[Educational entertainment|edutainment]]. Many events scheduled for Spring 2020 have been canceled because of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronovirus pandemic]].<ref>[https://www.happycow.net/events Happy Cow Vegan Festival Calendar, accessed 4/2/2020]</ref>\n\n== Africa ==\n=== Ghana ===\nVegfest 2015 was organized by the Vegetarian Association of Ghana.<ref name=\"wnyvegfest1\">{{cite web|title = WNY VegFest|url = http://www.wnyvegfest.com//|accessdate = 26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Asia ==\n=== Hong Kong ===\nHong Kong Vegfest started in 2013 organized by the Hong Kong Vegan Association. The festival organisers stipulate only vegan products be offered at the event by vendors. Admission is free to attendees.\n\n=== Indonesia ===\nThe first Bali Vegan Festival started in 2015 at Down To Earth (Ubud).<ref>{{cite web|title=Bali Vegan Festival|url=http://www.baliveganfestival.com/|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Japan ===\nThe Vegetarian Festival in Tokyo started in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tokyo Vegefood Fiesta|url=http://tokyo-vegefest.com/english/|website=Tokyo-vegefest.com|accessdate=21 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015041509/http://tokyo-vegefest.com/english/|archive-date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nThe Philippines had its first 3-leg vegan festival \u2013 VegFest Pilipinas \u2013 in November and December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=VegFest Pilipinas|url=http://vegfestpilipinas.com/|website=Vegfestpilipinas.com|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 2017 event was two 2-day VegFest Pilipinas events at two different locations: from 18\u201319 November 2017 in Eastwood City, with 'Hair,' Pilita in concert, and VegFest Pilipinas in Chinatown the following weekend, 25\u201326 November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegfestpilipinas.strikingly.com/|title=VegFest Pilipinas on Strikingly|author=|date=|website=VegFest Pilipinas|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astigvegan.com/vegfest-pilipinas-2017/|title=Enriquez RG. VegFest Pilipinas 2017, A Recap of what happened. December 8, 2017|author=|date=|website=astigvegan.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  The 2018 event again will be two 2-day VegFest Pilipinas events at two different locations: held one weekend from 8 am to 10 pm, 18\u201319 November 2018, at the BGC Arts Center in the Eastwood Central Plaza Shopping Mall, [[Quezon City]], [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]]; then again, the following weekend, 25\u201326 November 2017, in Lucky Chinatown, Binondo, [[Metro Manila]], [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/VegFestPilipinas/posts/|title=VegFest Pilipinas|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Singapore ===\n{{see also|EarthFest (SG)}}\nThe [[EarthFest (SG)|EarthFest Singapore]] had its debut in September 2015 and was sponsored by Singapore's [[Vegetarian Society (Singapore)|Vegetarian Society]] and others.\n\n=== Thailand ===\nThe Vegetarian Festival in Bangkok takes place each fall.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Vegetarian Festival|url=http://www.bangkok.com/whats-on-events/vegetarian-festival.htm|website=Bangkok.com|accessdate=23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{see also|Nine Emperor Gods Festival#Celebration in Thailand}}\nThis vegetarian festival is a nine-day period in October that celebrates the abstinence from meat during the ninth lunar month of the Chinese calendar.\n\n=== Vietnam ===\nThe Vegan Festival in Ho Chi Minh City takes place under the name Plant Power Celebration. The first one was held on 30 October 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/saigonveganfestival/|title=Saigon Vegan Festival|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Europe ==\n{{see also|Veganmania|VeggieWorld}}\n\n=== Belgium ===\nVegan Summer Fest is organized by BE Vegan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Summer Fest|url=http://bevegan.be/vegan-summer-fest/|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Czechia ===\n[[Fluff Fest]] is an independent [[hardcore punk]] festival held each July in [[Rokycany]]. It is fully vegan, with catering provided by local animal rights organization Svoboda zv\u00ed\u0159at.<ref name=\"idioteq2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.idioteq.com/a-look-inside-fluff-fest-exclusive-interview/|title=A Look Inside Fluff Fest!|first=Karol|last=Kami\u0144ski|publisher=Idioteq|date=28 January 2013|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Greece ===\nThe Vegan Life Festival (veganlife.gr) is a celebration in several Greek cities that presents vegan lifestyles, products, and practices through speeches, workshops, brochures, stalls with companies that provide vegan products, activities for children, and vegan food and sweets.  Admission open to the general public is free.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athensculturenet.com/en/event/vegan-life-festival-athens-2018|title=The Vegan Life Festival. Athens Culture Net. Accessed 12/26/2018|author=|date=|website=athensculturenet.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.veganlife.gr/|title=Veganlife|author=|date=|website=Veganlife|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  YouTube video documentation is available.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWEP-c1VWkxt5Hcd6WQFSJw|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=YouTube|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Athens ====\nThe Vegan Life Festival has been held in several cities in Greece since November 5, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/%CF%84%CE%B5%CF%87%CE%BD%CF%8C%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%BB%CE%B9%CF%82-%CE%B4%CE%AE%CE%BC%CE%BF%CF%85-%CE%B1%CE%B8%CE%B7%CE%BD%CE%B1%CE%AF%CF%89%CE%BD/vegan-life-festival-2016/178401362613208/|title=Vegan Life Festival 2016|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> The 2017 Vegan Life Festival was held in Athens on July 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.veganeventhub.com/event/vegan-life-festival-athens-2017/|title=Vegan Life Festival Athens 2017|author=|date=6 June 2017|website=veganeventhub.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> Buildout plans for nine Greek cities are being implemented gradually.  Organizers claim an attendance of greater than 18,000 visitors{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} at the 2018 Athens event, held at the Technopolis of the Municipality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutfestivals.gr/en/festivals/vegan-life-festival-2/|title=Vegan Life Festival 2018|author=|date=|website=allaboutfestivals.gr|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/veganlifefestival/vegan-life-festival-athens-2018/2058390741104185/|title=Vegan Life Festival Athens 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/veganlifefestival/events|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vegevents.com/events/vegan-life-festival/|title=Vegan Life Festival|author=|date=|website=Veg Events|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.happycow.net/reviews/vegan-life-festival-athens-142276 Vegan Life Festival/  HappyCow.net.  Accessed 12/26/2018]</ref>\n\n==== Thessaloniki ====\nVegan Life Festival since 2017.  The 2018 was held May 20. 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://livingcrueltyfree.gr/en/vegan-life-festival-thessaloniki-2018/|title=VEGAN LIFE FESTIVAL THESSALONIKI 2018!|last=Zoe|date=11 May 2018|website=livingcrueltyfree.gr|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Chania ====\nThe Vegan Life Festival is scheduled to begin in Chania in 2019.\n\n==== Malta ====\nFrom August 5\u20136, 2018, the Vegan Life Festival was held at The Floriana Granaries in Malta.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veganguidegreece.com/vegan-life-festival/|title=Vegan Life Festival \u2013 Vegan Guide Greece|author=|date=|website=veganguidegreece.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\nDublin Vegfest is the Irish capital's vegan festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dublinvegfest.com/|title=22nd & 23rd September 2018 \u2013 Dublin Vegfest|website=dublinvegfest.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\nVeganFest Bologna is a vegan event in Europe which had more than 43,000 visitors in 2014. The event took place in [[Bologna]] in September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=VeganFest Bologna|url=http://www.veganfest.it/?page_id=5188|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\nFestival The Vegetarian Chance (www.thevegetarianchance.org) was founded in 2014 by journalist Gabriel Eschenazi and chef Pietro Leemann. First Festival in the world which includes a haute cuisine vegan contest with international chefs. Out of the contest the program includes show cookings, lectures, movies and a small market. Five editions were held in Milan and the last one in Turin (11-13 October). Next edition will be held on 24-25-26 October in Milan.\n\n=== Hungary ===\n\n==== Budapest ====\nThe XIX Vegetarian Festival was organized in August 2015 in [[Budapest]]. {{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n=== Netherlands ===\n[[File:Psyfi.jpg|thumb|[[Psy-Fi]] in Leeuwarden, Netherlands]]\n* [[VeggieWorld]] in [[Utrecht]], since 2016, vegan<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nos.nl/op3/artikel/2090859-gaat-het-nieuwe-vlees-het-oude-vlees-verslaan.html |title=Gaat het nieuwe vlees het oude vlees verslaan? |work=NOS |date=5 March 2016 |accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Nederlandse Vereniging voor Veganisme|VegFest]] in Utrecht, since 2014, vegan<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/naakte-demonstranten-op-de-bres-voor-veganisme~afe5eb72/ |title=Naakte demonstranten op de bres voor veganisme |author=Amber Dujardin |work=Trouw |date=1 November 2014 |accessdate=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n* Veggie Fair in [[Lisserbroek]], since 2013, vegetarian<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.veganisme.org/event/veggiefair/ |title=VeggieFair 2016 |publisher=Nederlandse Vereniging voor Veganisme |accessdate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following music festivals have made a conscious decision not to sell any meat on the festival terrain: Digital Festival (DGTL) in [[Amsterdam]] (since 2016),<ref name=\"verbaasd\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/nederland/artikel/4208246/festival-milkshake-verbaasd-over-heftige-reacties-op-vegetarisch |title=Festival Milkshake verbaasd over heftige reacties op vegetarisch eten |work=RTL Nieuws |date=27 May 2018 |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"UITgezocht\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nu.nl/uit/5291708/uitgezocht-worden-festivals-vleesvrij.html |title=UITgezocht: Worden festivals vleesvrij? |work=NU.nl |date=31 May 2018 |accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref> Lente Kabinet in [[Oostzaan]] (since 2018),<ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/> Festival Milkshake in Amsterdam (since 2018),<ref name=\"verbaasd\"/><ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/> and [[Psy-Fi]] in [[Leeuwarden]] (starting from 2019).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.lc.nl/friesland/article24264539.ece |title=Psy-Fi verduurzaamt verder: volgende editie volledig vegetarisch |author=Yme Gietema |work=Leeuwarder Courant |date=13 March 2019 |accessdate=28 March 2019 |language=nl}}</ref> Organisers indicated their motives were sustainability and environmental protection; aside from dropping meat sales, they also focused on reducing the use of [[disposable product]]s and electricity.<ref name=\"verbaasd\"/><ref name=\"UITgezocht\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\n\n==== Alicante ====\nVegan Fest [[Alicante]] has been organized by Alacant Rock since 2014. It is the only vegan festival in [[Spain]]. {{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n=== Portugal ===\n\n==== Lisbon ====\nVegan\u00e1rio Fest [[Lisbon]] (www.veganario.org) has been organized since 2008 by a group of friends in punk/hardcore community with help of local HareKrishna Community. It is the oldest of its kind in Lisbon and has been growing in the last years. \nIt gathers a lot of organizations and small businesses and important people in the vegan community to talk about and spread veganism.\n\nThe music slowed down, it is more open to all the people. It is growing: Approximately 300/600px until 2014, more than 1500 in 2015, over 2000 in 2016, and more than 3500 in 2017.\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n==== ''England'' ==== \n===== Birmingham =====\nBirmingham Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\">[https://www.viva.org.uk/festivals/contact#contact Contact form for VIVA's Vegan Festivals, which supplement previously existing vegan festivals in UK]</ref>\n\n===== Bournemouth =====\nApproximately 90 stalls, talks, and food.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511025420/http://www.dorsetveganevents.co.uk/bournemouthveganfair.html|title=Bournemouth Vegan Fair \u2013 17 & 18 June 2017 \u2013 Dorset Vegan Events|author=|date=11 May 2017|website=web.archive.org|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Bradford =====\nBradford Vegan Festival was held on Sunday 2 September 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Community/veganfestivaluk/posts/|title=Bradford Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> and again will be held in September 2019.\n\n===== Brighton =====\nBrighton Vegan Festival took place on Saturday 14 July 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/brightonveganfestival2018/|title=Brighton Vegan & Ethical Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> and again will occur in July 2019.\n\nBrighton Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Bristol, Brighton, London =====\n{{see also|Vegfest (UK)}}\nVegfestUK Bristol was held May 26\u201327 at Ashton Gate stadium, Ashton Road, BS3 2EJ Bristol, United Kingdom.  Standard advance day tickets are \u00a311.00 (adults), \u00a36.00 (concessions) [including booking fees] and \u00a35.50 (children)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/ashton-gate-stadium/vegfestuk-bristol-2018/713055975565881/|title=VegfestUK Bristol 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://accounts.google.com/ServiceLogin?passive=1209600&osid=1&continue=https://plus.google.com/communities/111382870961138557305&followup=https://plus.google.com/communities/111382870961138557305|title=Sign in \u2013 Google Accounts|website=accounts.google.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> but was actually held from October 27\u201328, 2018, at Olympia London. The announcement was made in September 2018, citing higher than expected costs and broad availability of good quality vegan food in Bristol, that VegFestUK organizers would not schedule another event in Bristol for 2019 or 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/ashton-gate-stadium/vegfestuk-bristol-2018/713055975565881/|title=VegfestUK Bristol 2018|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/vegfestexpress/2018/09/statement-on-the-future-of-vegfestuk-bristol|title=Statement on the future of VegfestUK Bristol|website=Statement on the future of VegfestUK Bristol|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> but that VegFestUK would continue to hold annual events elsewhere.\n\n===== Coventry =====\nCoventry Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Liverpool =====\nLiverpool Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== London =====\nJustVShow is held in July<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.justvshow.co.uk|title=Just V Show \u2013 Vegan & Vegetarian Show in London & Glasgow|website=Just V Show}}</ref> and [[Vegfest (UK)|Vegfest]] (14,500 visitors in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vegfest.co.uk/our-events/|title=Our events|website=VegfestUK|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>) is held in autumn. Plant Powered Expo takes place for the first time in February 2020, just after [[Veganuary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.plantpoweredexpo.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Plant Powered Expo|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nLondon Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Kent =====\nMaidstone Vegan Festival took place for the second time on July 29, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maidstoneveganfestival.co.uk/|title=Maidstone Vegan Festival|website=Maidstoneveganfestival.co.uk|language=English|access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>\n\n===== Newcastle =====\nNewcastle Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 1 July 2018 from 10:30 AM \u2013 4:30 PM UTC+01 in Newcastle upon Tyne.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/newcastleveganfest|title=Newcastle Vegan Festival|website=https://www.facebook.com/newcastleveganfest|language=English|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/Causes/newcastle-vegan-festival-2018-vegan-awards/1645580835499105/|title=Newcastle VEGAN Festival 2018 + Vegan Awards|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Nottingham =====\nNottingham Viva! Vegan Festival<ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Sheffield =====\nSheffield Vegan Festival will be held on Saturday 15 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/sheffieldveganfestival/|title=Sheffield Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== ''Scotland'' ====\n===== Aberdeen =====\nAberdeen Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 8 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/aberdeenveganfest/|title=Aberdeen Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Cardiff =====\nCardiff Vegan Festival occurred on Saturday 22 September 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/cardiffveganfestival/|title=Log In or Sign Up to View|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"viva.org.uk\"/>\n\n===== Edinburgh =====\nEdinburgh Vegan Festival took place on Sunday 19 August 2018 in Murrayfield Stadium.  This is the first annual Edinburgh Vegan Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/edinburghveganfest/|title=Edinburgh Vegan Festival|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://veganfestival.co.uk/edinburgh-schools-vegan/|title=Edinburgh Schools Have Gone Plant Based|author=|date=25 April 2018|website=veganfestival.co.uk|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===== Glasgow =====\nJustVShow is held in July.<ref name=\"auto\"/>  The Glasgow JustVShow is scheduled for July 2\u20133, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justvshow.co.uk/scotland/|title=Just V Show \u2013 Vegan & Vegetarian Show in Glasgow|website=Glasgow, Scotland, Just V Show}}</ref>  In 2018 the JustVShow is co-locating with The Allergy & Free From Show Scotland 2018.\n\n== North America ==\n\n=== Canada ===\n====Alberta====\n=====Edmonton=====\nThe first Edmonton VegFest was held from 10 am to 6 pm on September 30, 2018, at the Ritchie Community League Hall and Outdoor Park, \n7727 98th Street Northwest, Edmonton, Alberta T6E 5C9. Admission was free. The nonprofit organization coordinating and hosting this annual event was Vegans and Vegetarians of Alberta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edmontonjournal.com/life/food/new-vegetable-festival-launches-in-ritchie-with-fun-shopping-and-greens|title=New Edmonton vegetable festival in Ritchie offers shopping, greens \u2013 Edmonton Journal|first1=Liane|last1=Faulder|date=20 September 2018|website=edmontonjournal.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todocanada.ca/vegfest-edmonton/|title=VegFest Edmonton \u2013 Ritchie Community League Hall & Park, 7727 98 Street Northwest, Edmonton|author=|date=|website=To Do Canada|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infoedmonton.com/event/vegfest/|title=VegFest|date=22 August 2019|website=InfoEdmonton|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/vegfest-edmonton-2018/182759825765331/|title=VegFest Edmonton 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/vvoaclub/|title=Vegans and Vegetarians of Alberta|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Ontario====\n=====Guelph=====\nVegfest Guelph<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegfestguelph.ca|title=Vegfest Guelph|website=Vegfest Guelph}}</ref> is an annual festival. The 2016 festival took place on Sunday, September 25, 2016, at Goldie Mill and the Guelph Youth Music Centre.\n\n=====Toronto=====\nThe Vegetarian Food Festival in Toronto attracted over 50,000 attendees in 2014 and featured more than 120 food and product vendors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegetarian Food Festival Toronto|url=http://veg.ca/festival|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> It is a free public festival held at Harbourfront Centre by the [[Toronto Vegetarian Association]] in Toronto the second weekend of every September.  It was first held in 1985 and is believed to be the largest and longest continuously running vegetarian food festival in North America, and is credited with having inspired the broad vegetarian food festival movement in the United States, which was first copied by the long-running [[Boston Vegetarian Society|Boston Vegetarian Food Festival]].\n\nThe Toronto Vegan Food and Drink Festival, a fully vegan food and drink festival in the city, strives to present an all vegan experience featuring comfort food, craft brews, wine and spirits.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vegan Food and Drink Festival Toronto|url=https://www.vegandrinkfest.com/toronto/}}</ref>\n\nThe Toronto Vegan Expo (formerly known as Vegan Spring Expo) was a free annual vegan festival that took place in Toronto from 2011 to 2013 and had an attendee record of 1500 in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.veganspringexpo.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222123329/http://www.veganspringexpo.com/|url-status=dead|title=502 Bad Gateway nginx openresty 185.15.56.1|archivedate=22 December 2014|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=====Niagara (St. Catharines)=====\nNiagara VegFest began in 2012 and is an annual event that takes place in downtown St. Catharines, Ontario.<ref>{{cite web|title=Niagara VegFest|url=http://niagaravegfest.com|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> The 2012 Niagara VegFest closed with a screening of [[Vegucated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getvegucated.com/ |title=Vegucated |publisher=Getvegucated.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-17}}</ref>\n\n=====Ottawa=====\nThe first Ottawa Veg Fest was held in 2009, and was organized by the National Capital Vegetarian Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ottawa Veg Fest|url=http://vegfest.ca|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=====Kingston=====\nThe first Kingston Veg Fest was held in the fall of 2016. It is being organized by the Kingston Vegetarian Network<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingston Vegetarian Network|url=http://kingstonveg.ca |accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=====Mississauga=====\nThe first Mississauga Veg Fest was held in May 2018. Mississauga Veg Fest was the city's first vegan festival! Over 60 vendors were in attendance to showcase the GTHA's finest veg-based food, drink, clothing & accessories, products, advocate groups and children's activities. It is being organized by a private volunteer committee<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississauga Veg Fest|url=https://mississaugavegfest.ca |accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=====Muskoka=====\nMuskoka VegFest had its inaugural event on Aug 11, 2018. 68 Vendors and various speakers drew in a crowd of just under 5000 people.  The annual event is run by a private volunteer committee.  It is a not-for profit event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Muskoka Veg Fest|url=http://muskokavegfest.com|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Quebec====\n=====Montreal=====\nThe first Montreal Vegan Festival was held from September 26\u201327, 2014 and welcomed over 5,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://festivalveganedemontreal.com/2014en/|title=2014\u2013 Montreal Vegan Festival \u2013 September 26\u201327, 2014|website=2014\u2013 Montreal Vegan Festival}}</ref>\n\n====M\u00e9xico====\n\n=====Baja California=====\n\nTijuana Veggie Fest 2018 was held on July 6, 2018, in Centro Cultural Tijuana (CECUT), Paseo de los H\u00e9roes No. 9350, Zona Urbana R\u00edo, Tijuana, Baja California.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/tjveggiefest/tijuana-veggie-fest-2018/148377289195497/|title=Tijuana Veggie Fest 2018|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref>  Tijuana Veggie Fest 2019 is tentatively scheduled for June 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/VeggieFestTijuana/|title=Tijuana Veggie Fest 2019 Fac